From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
Date: Sat, 30 May 2026 03:20:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fman_port: add dormant fman_port_set_rx_bpool() reprogram
 primitive (M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 4, write mechanism, no caller)

M3-3 step 7 (true zero-copy RX, spec sec 6.1.7) has a three-mechanism
plan: (1) Recognise XSK-pool-sourced FDs (fd->bpid == priv->xsk_bpid[band],
landed observational as xsk_zc_eligible, patch 0093); (2) Recover the
xdp_buff from the XSK chunk instead of build_skb() (read side landed
dormant as xsk_zc_rx_recovered, patch 0096); (3) reProgram the FMan RX
port's primary BMan pool ID from the kernel page-pool BPID
(priv->dpaa_bp->bpid) to the dedicated XSK pool BPID
(priv->xsk_bpid[band]) so FMan DMAs directly into XSK chunks (read side
landed dormant as xsk_zc_rx_armed, patch 0094).

Mechanism 3's WRITE is the single hardware-riskiest action in the entire
step-7 plan: spec sec 6.1.8 records three under-load DUT crashes from XSK
RX work (list_add free-list corruption in xp_alloc(), a dcache_clean_poc
paging fault, a 52 s soft-lockup). Per spec sec 6.1.12 the WRITE must not
fire until the read-side gate counters are DUT-confirmed under a live
XDP_ZEROCOPY bind: xsk_zc_rx_armed > 0 (distinct reprogram target) AND
xsk_fill_guard_block == 0 (FILL-ring single-producer invariant holds).

Surveying mainline 6.18.31 confirms there is NO exported API to reprogram
a live FMan RX port's BMan pool: set_bpools() (fman_port.c:744, writes the
BMI FMBM_REBM/bpool register set) and its caller set_ext_buffer_pools()
(fman_port.c:891) are both `static` and run exactly once during
fman_port_init(). The bpool table itself lives in
port->cfg->ext_buf_pools.ext_buf_pool[] (struct fman_ext_pool_params
{ u8 id; u16 size; }, fman.h:171). fman_port_disable()/fman_port_enable()
ARE exported (fman_port.h:121/123) and are already used by the dpaa
detach path (dpaa_eth.c:332) and the XSK pool detach sequence (spec
sec 6.1.1 step 3) to quiesce the BMI before touching pool state.

This patch lands the durable in-tree WRITE primitive, DORMANT:

  int fman_port_set_rx_bpool(struct fman_port *port, u8 old_bpid,
                             u8 new_bpid);

It walks port->cfg->ext_buf_pools.ext_buf_pool[], swaps the entry whose
.id == old_bpid to new_bpid (preserving .size), and re-invokes
set_ext_buffer_pools() to rewrite the BMI bpool registers from the
mutated cfg. The caller is REQUIRED to have already fman_port_disable()d
the RX port (the BMI must be quiesced before its pool registers are
rewritten) and to fman_port_enable() it afterwards -- exactly the
disable/enable bracket the XSK detach sequence already establishes. The
function validates: non-NULL port, RX port type, old_bpid actually
present in the table (else -ENOENT, so a mis-paired call can never
silently corrupt an unrelated pool slot), and new_bpid != old_bpid
(else -EALREADY, idempotent no-op rejection).

Why land it dormant now, with NO caller:

  - It is the last *mechanism* of the three-mechanism plan to land. After
    0093 (Recognise), 0094 (reProgram read), 0095 (FILL guard), 0096
    (Recover read), every read side plus the FILL-ring crash guard is in
    tree; this adds the reviewable WRITE body without firing it. The
    productive call-site wiring (invoke fman_port_set_rx_bpool() inside
    the af_xdp_pool attach disable/enable bracket, then flip the dormant
    0096 Recover branch to xsk_buff/xdp_do_redirect()) becomes the FINAL
    sub-increment, authored ONLY after spec sec 6.1.12's gate counters
    are DUT-confirmed non-zero under a real ZC producer.

  - It mirrors the exact cadence every prior offload primitive followed:
    fman_hm_node_install (0090) and fman_policer_install (0091) shipped
    as exported entry points with no productive caller before their
    bodies (0099/0100) and consumers landed. A reviewable, compiled,
    EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL'd primitive with zero call sites is the standard
    de-risking step here.

Why this is byte-identical to mainline on every flavor: the symbol is
exported but called by nobody in this patch, so no FMan register is ever
written by it. The RX/TX datapaths, the af_xdp_pool attach/detach paths,
and fman_port_init() are all untouched. `nm` will show the export; the
running kernel behaves exactly as the 0101 build does.

Spec sec 6.1.7 true-ZC mechanism 3 (reProgram, WRITE primitive) +
sec 6.1.11 / sec 6.1.12.

v2 (persistent-table fix): the original v1 body operated on
port->cfg->ext_buf_pools and re-invoked the static set_ext_buffer_pools().
fman_port_init() does kfree(port->cfg); port->cfg = NULL; at the end of
init, so on a LIVE post-init RX port port->cfg is NULL. v1 therefore
dereferenced a freed/NULL cfg at attach time and set_ext_buffer_pools()
(which also reads port->cfg->{ext_buf_pools,buf_pool_depletion}) saw
garbage, making set_bpools() reject the live re-commit with -EINVAL (-22)
-- the exact failure observed on DUT 192.168.1.190 with the productive
0103b caller. v2 operates on the PERSISTENT port->ext_buf_pools (memcpy'd
into struct fman_port during init, survives the kfree) and rebuilds the
BMI bpool registers by calling the static set_bpools() directly, bypassing
the dead-cfg dereference. set_bpools() reads only persistent state
(port->ext_pools_num, port->port_type, port->bmi_regs, plus its bp arg).

Signed-off-by: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.c
index 255360d..91de052 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.c
@@ -962,6 +962,122 @@ static int set_ext_buffer_pools(struct fman_port *port)
 	return 0;
 }
 
+/**
+ * fman_port_set_rx_bpool() - reprogram a live RX port's primary BMan pool ID
+ * @port: the FMan RX port (mac_dev->port[RX])
+ * @old_bpid: the BPID currently programmed into the port's bpool table
+ *	  (normally the kernel page-pool BPID, priv->dpaa_bp->bpid)
+ * @new_bpid: the BPID to swap in (normally the dedicated XSK pool BPID,
+ *	  priv->xsk_bpid[band])
+ *
+ * M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 4 (patch 0102): the WRITE half of mechanism 3
+ * (reProgram) in the true-ZC RX plan (spec sec 6.1.7). Mutates the port's
+ * PERSISTENT external-buffer-pool table (port->ext_buf_pools.ext_buf_pool[])
+ * by replacing the entry whose .id == @old_bpid with @new_bpid (the .size is
+ * preserved), then rewrites the BMI bpool registers via set_bpools(). After
+ * this, FMan RX BMI DMAs ingress frames into @new_bpid.
+ *
+ * IMPORTANT (the 0103b -22 root cause): this MUST operate on the persistent
+ * port->ext_buf_pools, NOT on port->cfg->ext_buf_pools. fman_port_init()
+ * does kfree(port->cfg); port->cfg = NULL; (see end of fman_port_init), so
+ * on a live post-init port port->cfg is NULL. The init-time helper
+ * set_ext_buffer_pools() reads port->cfg->{ext_buf_pools,buf_pool_depletion}
+ * and therefore cannot be reused here -- it would dereference the freed cfg
+ * and the resulting garbage num_of_pools_used / non-ascending sizes make
+ * set_bpools() reject the live re-commit with -EINVAL. We instead rebuild
+ * the ordered bpools struct from the persistent table and call set_bpools()
+ * directly (set_bpools() touches only persistent state: port->ext_pools_num,
+ * port->port_type, port->bmi_regs, and its bp argument).
+ *
+ * CONTRACT: the caller MUST have already fman_port_disable()d @port before
+ * calling this (the BMI must be quiesced before its pool registers are
+ * rewritten) and MUST fman_port_enable() it afterwards -- the same
+ * disable/enable bracket the XSK pool detach sequence (spec sec 6.1.1)
+ * already establishes around fman_port_disable(rxp).
+ *
+ * Pool-depletion (FMBM_RMPD) is intentionally left as init programmed it:
+ * swapping the primary pool's BPID does not change depletion topology, and
+ * the depletion config lived in the now-freed port->cfg.
+ *
+ * Returns 0 on success, -EINVAL on a NULL or non-RX port, -ENOENT if
+ * @old_bpid is not present in the port's pool table, -EALREADY if
+ * @new_bpid == @old_bpid, or the set_bpools() error otherwise.
+ */
+int fman_port_set_rx_bpool(struct fman_port *port, u8 old_bpid, u8 new_bpid)
+{
+	struct fman_ext_pools *ext_pools;
+	u8 ordered_array[FMAN_PORT_MAX_EXT_POOLS_NUM];
+	u16 sizes_array[BM_MAX_NUM_OF_POOLS];
+	struct fman_port_bpools bpools;
+	int i, slot = -1, err;
+
+	if (!port || port->port_type != FMAN_PORT_TYPE_RX)
+		return -EINVAL;
+
+	if (new_bpid == old_bpid)
+		return -EALREADY;
+
+	/* Use the PERSISTENT pool table -- port->cfg was freed at init. */
+	ext_pools = &port->ext_buf_pools;
+
+	for (i = 0; i < ext_pools->num_of_pools_used; i++) {
+		if (ext_pools->ext_buf_pool[i].id == old_bpid) {
+			slot = i;
+			break;
+		}
+	}
+
+	if (slot < 0) {
+		dev_err(port->dev,
+			"%s: old_bpid %u not present in RX pool table\n",
+			__func__, old_bpid);
+		return -ENOENT;
+	}
+
+	ext_pools->ext_buf_pool[slot].id = new_bpid;
+
+	/* Rebuild the BMI bpool registers from the persistent table without
+	 * going through set_ext_buffer_pools() (which reads the freed cfg).
+	 */
+	memset(ordered_array, 0, sizeof(ordered_array));
+	memset(sizes_array, 0, sizeof(sizes_array));
+	fman_sp_set_buf_pools_in_asc_order_of_buf_sizes(ext_pools,
+						       ordered_array,
+						       sizes_array);
+
+	memset(&bpools, 0, sizeof(bpools));
+	bpools.count = ext_pools->num_of_pools_used;
+	bpools.counters_enable = true;
+	for (i = 0; i < ext_pools->num_of_pools_used; i++) {
+		bpools.bpool[i].bpid = ordered_array[i];
+		bpools.bpool[i].size = sizes_array[ordered_array[i]];
+	}
+
+	/* Keep rx_pools_params consistent for any later size-dependent path. */
+	port->rx_pools_params.num_of_pools = ext_pools->num_of_pools_used;
+	port->rx_pools_params.largest_buf_size =
+		sizes_array[ordered_array[ext_pools->num_of_pools_used - 1]];
+
+	err = set_bpools(port, &bpools);
+	if (err) {
+		/* roll the cached table back so a retry sees a consistent
+		 * state; set_bpools() commits registers only after its
+		 * ascending-order validation passes.
+		 */
+		ext_pools->ext_buf_pool[slot].id = old_bpid;
+		dev_err(port->dev,
+			"%s: set_bpools() failed (%d), bpid reverted\n",
+			__func__, err);
+		return err;
+	}
+
+	dev_info(port->dev,
+	 "fman_port: RX primary bpool reprogrammed %u -> %u\n",
+	 old_bpid, new_bpid);
+	return 0;
+}
+EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_port_set_rx_bpool);
+
 static int init_low_level_driver(struct fman_port *port)
 {
 	struct fman_port_cfg *cfg = port->cfg;
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.h b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.h
index 129dcc3..cc39538 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_port.h
@@ -124,6 +124,15 @@ int fman_port_enable(struct fman_port *port);
 
 u32 fman_port_get_qman_channel_id(struct fman_port *port);
 
+/* M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 4 (patch 0102): reprogram a live RX port's
+ * primary BMan pool ID (the WRITE half of true-ZC mechanism 3, spec
+ * sec 6.1.7). The caller MUST fman_port_disable() the port first and
+ * fman_port_enable() it afterwards. DORMANT as of 0102 (exported, no
+ * caller); the productive af_xdp_pool attach call site is the gated
+ * final sub-increment (spec sec 6.1.12).
+ */
+int fman_port_set_rx_bpool(struct fman_port *port, u8 old_bpid, u8 new_bpid);
+
 int fman_port_get_hash_result_offset(struct fman_port *port, u32 *offset);
 
 int fman_port_get_tstamp(struct fman_port *port, const void *data, u64 *tstamp);
-- 
